She began her teaching career at the high school level in the 1990s, and this experience motivated her to study more about how people learn another language. She then moved to Australia and received her Master's degree in applied linguistics from Monash University in 2004. After that she returned to Japan and worked as a research associate at Waseda University, where she was in charge of writing consultations at the Writing Center. In 2006, she was awarded the Fulbright Scholarship and moved to the United States to pursue a doctoral degree.
